  "prompt": "How does one become a dentist in Canada?",
  "response": "To become a dentist in Canada, you'll need to follow these steps:\n\n1. Complete High School\n- Focus on science courses like biology and chemistry\n\n2. Undergraduate Degree\n- Earn a 4-year bachelor's degree (preferably in science)\n- Complete prerequisite courses for dental school\n\n3. Dental School\n- Apply to and complete a 4-year Doctor of Dental Surgery (DDS) or Doctor of Dental Medicine (DMD) program\n- Be accepted through a competitive admissions process\n- Programs are offered at universities like University of Toronto, University of British Columbia, McGill University\n\n4. National Dental Examining Board of Canada (NDEB)\n- Pass the NDEB equivalency process (for internationally trained dentists)\n- Complete written and clinical examinations\n\n5. Provincial Licensing\n- Apply for licensure with the dental regulatory body in your province\n- Meet specific provincial requirements\n- Pass provincial examination if required\n\n6. Optional Specialization\n- Complete additional 2-3 year residency in a specific dental specialty (optional)\n\n7. Continuing Education\n- Maintain license through ongoing professional development\n- Complete required continuing education credits\n\nTotal time: Approximately 8-10 years from high school to becoming a licensed dentist.",
